They stand out from the rest of his work, and are easily recognized. In old writings such sentences are often marked by a hand in the margin, to denote that they are worthy of more than passing consideration3 or they might be put between inverted commas, to emphasize their wit or wisdom. Sometimes they are brought in very awkwardly, and do not harmonize with surrounding matter3 and sometimes the speakers follow up their wise saws by remarks which indicate very plainly that they are conscious of having given utterance to something beyond the common. But, whether awkwardly introduced or otherwise, these notes, whether cast into the form of proverb-5 or shaped to rime, stand out from the text and rivet one's atten- tion. I will deal with some of these notes, and show that in many cases they should be put between in- verted commas, not merely to show up their wisdom or beauty, but because they are actually quotations pure and simple.
